│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The verifier reports 'Instruction does not dominate all uses!' for IR created │
│ by SLP. The error mentions vector.insert, insertelement, and shufflevector    │
│ with values like %15 and %13, indicating that SLP produces a subvector        │
│ insertion with llvm.vector.insert and then uses that value in a shuffle that  │
│ is positioned such that the defining instruction does not properly dominate   │
│ its uses across the CFG. This typically happens when a pass builds IR across  │
│ multiple blocks with inconsistent insertion points, or when a value is        │
│ defined in a block that does not dominate another block where it is used.     │
│                                                                               │
│ In this reproducer, SLP is building a widened vector from scalars with mixed  │
│ control-flow and PHIs. The SLP 'revec' path inserts fixed-vector pieces       │
│ (subvectors) into a larger vector using llvm.vector.insert at computed        │
│ positions, and then shuffles. The dominance error implies the newly created   │
│ vector_insert and/or the insertelement are being inserted in a block that     │
│ does not dominate the subsequent uses (e.g. the shuffle or a following        │
│ vector_insert), which is a sign of a misplacement of generated instructions.  │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The first visible issue is reported by the verifier when the pipeline runs.   │
│ The error points to:                                                          │
│ - %15 = call <6 x double> @llvm.vector.insert.v6f64.v2f64(...)                │
│ - %9 = shufflevector <6 x double> %15, ...                                    │
│ And similarly:                                                                │
│ - %13 = insertelement <2 x double> %12, double %1, i32 1                      │
│ - %11 = call <6 x double> @llvm.vector.insert.v6f64.v2f64(..., %13, ...)      │
│                                                                               │
│ The error indicates %15 and %13 are created in places that do not dominate    │
│ their users. In SLP logs, the routines involved are createInsertVector (emits │
│ vector_insert or shuffle) and CreateInsertElement (emits insertelement or     │
│ insert_subvector) with subsequent CreateShuffle. The code paths around line   │
│ ~16055 call createInsertVector when Scalar is a fixed vector type, capturing  │
│ the intrinsic and then later building shuffles. If insertion points differ or │
│ the intrinsic ends up in a block with tighter scope than its uses, dominance  │
│ breaks.                                                                       │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The core issue is the use of llvm.vector.insert (insert_subvector) in         │
│ SLPReVec without guaranteeing that the insertion point for the intrinsic is   │
│ in a block that dominates all subsequent uses produced by the builder. SLP is │
│ doing 'lazy' shuffle emission and mixes the creation of subvector inserts and │
│ shuffles across the reconstruction of a vector value from multiple lanes,     │
│ sometimes reusing 'Root' and then merging shuffles                            │
│ (ShuffleInstructionBuilder). When subvector indices align, createInsertVector │
│ chooses the intrinsic path unconditionally. However, because SLP is           │
│ reconstructing the full vector across multiple positions and potentially      │
│ different blocks, the intrinsic can be emitted in a later or non-dominating   │
│ block, while the shuffle or subsequent vector_insert that uses its result is  │
│ emitted earlier or in a dominating scope. This leads to the verifier          │
│ dominance failure.                                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ This class of bugs has been addressed previously by avoiding insert_subvector │
│ when IR placement becomes tricky or by always lowering subvector insertions   │
│ to shuffles under vectorizer-controlled insertion, which are easier to place  │
│ consistently. In our case, the simplest safe fix is to make                   │
│ createInsertVector always generate the shuffle-based insertion sequence       │
│ rather than emitting llvm.vector.insert directly. This ensures that all       │
│ generated operations are normal shuffles that can be placed consistently by   │
│ the Builder. Additionally, at the call site in CreateInsertElement, relying   │
│ on the intrinsic result (and inspecting it) is brittle; we can remove the     │
│ assumption of intrinsic and treat the returned value uniformly.               │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - Edit Point 1: Replace the intrinsic emission path in createInsertVector     │
│ with the always-shuffle-based implementation. That is, remove the             │
│ special-case that emits Builder.CreateInsertVector(... vector_insert ...)     │
│ when Index is a multiple of the subvector length, and always build the        │
│ resize+two-operand shuffle. This makes insertion deterministic and avoids     │
│ introducing a new call that later is used across blocks in a way that breaks  │
│ dominance.                                                                    │
│                                                                               │
│   File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp, Lines 5796-5821.     │
│   Change createInsertVector to:                                               │
│   - Remove the 'if (Index % SubVecVF == 0) { Vec =                            │
│ Builder.CreateInsertVector(...); } else { ... }' branching.                   │
│   - Always compute VecVF, Mask, and perform resizing of V to VecVF and then   │
│ CreateShuffleVector(Vec, V, Mask). If a Generator is provided, use it to      │
│ produce the shuffle, otherwise use the default path.                          │
│                                                                               │
│   Rationale: Ensures all insertions are represented as shuffles, keeping the  │
│ builder-inserted IR consistent and avoiding the placement of an intrinsic     │
│ that has different dominance properties. Shuffles are easier to maintain      │
│ within the current insertion point discipline.                                │
│                                                                               │
│ - Edit Point 2: In the call site of createInsertVector inside                 │
│ CreateInsertElement (lines 16055-16064), remove the logic that assumes the    │
│ returned value is an intrinsic vector_insert and records InsElt based on      │
│ dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>. Just treat the result uniformly as an Instruction    │
│ for tracking purposes, without depending on it being the intrinsic. This      │
│ prevents early returns and keeps GatherShuffleExtractSeq and CSEBlocks        │
│ tracking consistent.                                                          │
│                                                                               │
│   File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp, Lines 16055-16064.   │
│   Suggested changes:                                                          │
│   - After calling createInsertVector, set InsElt by                           │
│ dyn_cast<Instruction>(Vec) unconditionally for the fixed-vector case, do not  │
│ require Intrinsic::vector_insert.                                             │
│   - Remove the check 'if (!II || II->getIntrinsicID() !=                      │
│ Intrinsic::vector_insert) return Vec;' and instead proceed to record InsElt   │
│ if it is an Instruction.                                                      │
│                                                                               │
│   Rationale: With edit point 1, createInsertVector will no longer produce     │
│ vector_insert. The call-site shouldn't expect it, and must still track the    │
│ created instruction (shuffle) to maintain CSEBlocks and                       │
│ GatherShuffleExtractSeq, avoiding inconsistencies leading to misplaced IR.    │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By removing the intrinsic-based subvector insert emission and always lowering │
│ insertions to shuffle sequences inside createInsertVector, and by adjusting   │
│ the caller logic to not depend on vector_insert being returned, we avoid      │
│ generating IR that the pass places at non-dominating locations relative to    │
│ its subsequent uses. This eliminates the dominance violation detected by the  │
│ verifier for the given reproducer and stabilizes IR generation in SLP's       │
│ 'revec' reconstruction path. The functional behavior is preserved             │
│ (insert-subvector semantics via shuffles), while dominance and placement are  │
│ made predictable.                                                             │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
